{"questionId":"26560","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The straight metal arm of a windscreen wiper on a car rotates in a circular motion from a&nbsp;pivot point, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>O</mtext></math>, through an angle of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>140</mn><mo>°</mo></math>. The windscreen is cleared by a rubber blade of&nbsp;length <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>46</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math> that is attached to the metal arm between points <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math>. The total length&nbsp;of the metal arm, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>OB</mtext></math>, is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>56</mn><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p>The part of the windscreen cleared by the rubber blade is shown unshaded in the&nbsp;following diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/6c66ca1802e0297e2c41cb35527d664fbd6cd41d.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Determine the area of the windscreen that is cleared by the rubber blade.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>subtracting two substituted area of sectors formulae &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>140</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>360</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>56</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mn>140</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>360</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<strong>OR&nbsp; &nbsp;</strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>140</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>360</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>×</mo><mfenced><mrow><msup><mn>56</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>-</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3710</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>cm</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>3709</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>…</mo><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>cm</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"26560","referenceCode":"22M.1.SL.TZ2.1b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Determine the area of the windscreen that is cleared by the rubber blade.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.4—The circle, arc and area of sector, degrees only"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}